    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-02T22:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-02T22:00:00-05:00" n="830"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d830">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/11427: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Atcheson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-03T11:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 3, 1937—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 3—6 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>986. Embassy’s 982, December 2, noon and 978, December 1, 3 p.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Hsu Mo, political Vice Minister of Foreign Affairs and Counsellor of
                        German Embassy accompanied Trautmann here and left with him for Hankow at
                        midnight last night after conferring with Chiang Kai Shek. We are reliably
                        informed that (1) proposals communicated to Chiang by German Ambassador were
                        in general as set forth in our 978; (2) Chiang’s reply was substantially as
                        indicated in our 982 and; (3) Chiang has taken the position that (<hi
                            rend="italic">a</hi>) any negotiations must be undertaken with the
                        Chinese Foreign Office, (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) he will not <pb
                            facs="0756" n="749" xml:id="pg_749"/> recognize any settlement which
                        violates his stipulation concerning sovereignty and, (<hi rend="italic"
                            >c</hi>) in event of such settlement he will continue with his troops to
                        resist the Japanese.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Repeated to Hankow, Peiping, Shanghai. Peiping please repeat to
                        Tokyo.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Atcheson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
